<chapter>
<title>Tips and Tricks</title>

<section>
<title>Screenie</title>
<body>

<p>
Want to organize your command line screen session or sessions better?
Want to have a separate screen session for every task that you do?  Want 
something that will organize you in general?
</p>

<p>
This GWN has the perfect tip for you. It is a tiny script called screenie.
</p>

<pre caption="Getting Screenie">
# emerge screenie
</pre>

<p>
Start by running it.
</p>

<pre caption="Launching screenie">
# screenie
</pre>

<p>
You should see the following:
</p>

<pre caption="Adding a job">
SCREENIE - terminal screen-session handler
written by Marc O. Gloor &lt;mgloor&amp;fhzh.ch&gt;


a) add job
q) quit

select:
</pre>

<p>
Lets add a job called &quot;Systems&quot;. Once you hit a, enter the name you 
will be asked for the &quot;job&quot;. Hit enter unless you know the process id 
of existing screen sessions.
</p>

<p>
Lets add a second job called &quot;Email&quot;. You should see this:
</p>

<pre caption="Listing jobs">
SCREENIE - terminal screen-session handler
written by Marc O. Gloor &lt;mgloor&amp;fhzh.ch&gt;

1) 15468.Systems
2) 15504.Email

a) add job
q) quit

select:
</pre>

<p>
You now have two screen sessions that you can go into and out of. Select 
one of the sessions. You are now inside of screen where you can do whatever 
you usually do.
</p>

<note>
See the <uri link="http://www.gentoo.org/news/en/gwn/20030714-newsletter.xml#doc_chap9">
tips and tricks describing screen.</uri>
</note>

<p>
To go to another screen session, press CTRL+a+d (or however you usually exit 
your screen sessions).  You should be back to the screenie menu and ready to 
choose to go to another screen session.
</p>


<p>
One use of screenie might be to have a screen session for every task and for 
every machine you have access to making multi-tasking much more organized. This 
should also make it much easier to start working again after a long break.
</p>

</body>

</section>

